@Walter B As a law student, that's quite honestly hitting the nail on the head and something I've noticed on my case reviews as well.

The courts must (and should) follow due process.  I know you're only expressing frustration.
There are some challenges within the law.  The industry often talks about power structures.  For example, Johnny could use his fists to defend himself (we know how that would end), conversely, Amber could use a knife or similar weapon (as it often the case in domestic situations) to defend herself.  The court argues because males have more muscle mass on average (if biology is not disputed), then that creates a power imbalance which means that courts need to "factor" that imbalance in, creating these complex webs.  In the old days it used to be actus reus and mens rea (basically what did you do any why).  That was condemned as giving privilege to some.
Basically, it's a long-winded way of saying that equality before the law has been redefined and that rather than considering the crime and the motive, it's often couched as pre-determined power structures.  This obviously will depend on the judge presiding over the case.
If that sounds complicated, it's far more complicated than it should be.
